{"term":"1978","caseName":"Leo Sheep Company v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1978/77-1686","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 16, 1979","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger6/oral_argument_audio/16030","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Stewart.","start":0,"stop":1.07,"duration":1.07},{"text":"We'll resume arguments in Leo Sheep Company against the United States.","start":1.07,"stop":7.076,"duration":6.01},{"text":"Mrs. Beale.","start":7.076,"stop":13.841,"duration":6.77}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":13.841,"stop":16.726,"duration":2.89},{"text":"When Congress made the railroad land grants that reserved a total of approximately 100 million acres of public lands that were interspersed, checkerboard fashion with the lands that it had granted to the railroads.","start":16.726,"stop":29.51,"duration":12.78},{"text":"The railroad received the odd-numbered sections that completely surrounded each of the retained public sections.","start":29.51,"stop":36.656,"duration":7.15},{"text":"It's not possible to either enter or leave any of the retained public sections without passing over some portions of the lands that were granted to the railroads.","start":36.656,"stop":46.527,"duration":9.87},{"text":"The question before this Court is whether Congress reserved a legal and forcible right to enter and leave those 100 million acres of public lands.","start":46.527,"stop":58.293,"duration":11.77},{"text":"We submit that Congress' intent to reserve a right of access was manifest in the pattern and in the plan of the railroad grants.","start":58.293,"stop":67.459,"duration":9.17},{"text":"In the same way, as a private grant towards intention to reserve a right of access to lands that he retains when he makes a grant maybe implicit or manifest in the pattern of the grants.","start":67.459,"stop":80.325,"duration":12.87},{"text":"It was settled that common law that where a private grantor conveys away lands that completely surround another portion of lands that he retains.","start":80.325,"stop":89.109,"duration":8.78},{"text":"He is presumed or assumed to have reserved some right of access so that he can enter and leave that lands that he retained in order to make use of them.","start":89.109,"stop":98.261,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Who is the private landowner doesn't have the right of eminent domain, does he?","start":98.261,"stop":102.047,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's certainly true and one of the suggestions that the petitioners have made here is that perhaps Congress intended to first grant out these 100 million acres of land and then use the power of eminent domain in order to secure access to issued these checkerboard sections one by one.","start":102.047,"stop":120.423,"duration":18.38},{"text":"And we've suggested in our brief that it is inconceivable that Congress could have purposely intended to set up a pattern or a mechanism that would be -- that cumbersome and unworkable.","start":120.423,"stop":132.907,"duration":12.48},{"text":"It would have completely overpowered the state territorial and federal courts to have set up that kind of mechanism.","start":132.907,"stop":140.197,"duration":7.29},{"text":"And moreover, we can see from the history of the use of these grants that the Federal Government did not turnaround after making the grant and begin a concerted pattern of condemnation on these rights of way.","start":140.197,"stop":153.07,"duration":12.87},{"text":"So we think not only was that an unworkable way of gaining access to these lands but we find no evidence that that is what Congress either did intend in the legislative history and no evidence that that in fact is what occurred after the land grants were made.","start":153.07,"stop":168.994,"duration":15.92},{"text":"So although, it is true that Congress does that United States retained the right to use the power of eminent domain were necessary.","start":168.994,"stop":177.258,"duration":8.26},{"text":"We think that that really does not provide the key to interpreting what Congress intent was when it made that checkerboard pattern of land grants.","start":177.258,"stop":186.229,"duration":8.97}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mrs. Beale, I suppose it's well-established that the question of the construction of a federal grant is a federal question but what body of law does one turn to in deciding that federal question.","start":186.229,"stop":200.971,"duration":14.74},{"text":"Is it a general common law of real property?","start":200.971,"stop":204.886,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that that may provide some kind of basis for interpreting what Congress' intent is?","start":204.886,"stop":211.863,"duration":6.98},{"text":"Of course the general cases, teaching how to interpret the Acts applies.","start":211.863,"stop":218.993,"duration":7.13},{"text":"We would look to the legislative intent.","start":218.993,"stop":220.742,"duration":1.75},{"text":"We would look to the administrative construction.","start":220.742,"stop":222.9,"duration":2.16},{"text":"And we might also look to the context in which the grants were made, the historical context.","start":222.9,"stop":227.455,"duration":4.56},{"text":"And we might also look to the -- in doing now, we might look to the common law basis for land grants to see how one might interpret the intent of Congress.","start":227.455,"stop":238.047,"duration":10.59},{"text":"So I think all of those would provide a guide.","start":238.047,"stop":240.758,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you see --","start":240.758,"stop":241.159,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Are we -- excuse me, go ahead.","start":241.159,"stop":243.441,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you see any difference in the common law between an implied easement and easement of necessity?","start":243.441,"stop":251.137,"duration":7.7}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, one can try the things -- I should make our point here.","start":251.137,"stop":255.283,"duration":4.15},{"text":"We are not claiming that there was a common law easement of necessity created when Congress made these grants.","start":255.283,"stop":261.613,"duration":6.33},{"text":"What we are saying and this goes back to my prior answer you is that the assumption that underlies the common law rule about easements of necessity and that also plays a part in other kinds of implied easements about attempting to construe the intent of the parties.","start":261.613,"stop":278.711,"duration":17.1},{"text":"And about what the grantor's intent must have been in this kind of circumstance is the guide here.","start":278.711,"stop":284.995,"duration":6.28},{"text":"So we are not claiming a common law easement by necessity.","start":284.995,"stop":289.012,"duration":4.02},{"text":"What we are seeking to do is to ascertain the intent of Congress by looking to rules about common law easements by necessity and there are broader rules about easements by implications, so there are some differences.","start":289.012,"stop":301.378,"duration":12.37}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You're claiming reservation, aren't you?","start":301.378,"stop":303.955,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Of reserved --","start":303.955,"stop":304.305,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Not an easement by necessity, does it?","start":304.305,"stop":306.055,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly right.","start":306.055,"stop":306.931,"duration":0.88},{"text":"A reserved easement and implied --","start":306.931,"stop":307.97,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Since the grantee with the power of eminent domain can never show an easement by necessity because it -- there is no necessity.","start":307.97,"stop":314.761,"duration":6.79},{"text":"It can always condemn?","start":314.761,"stop":316.345,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, one could certainly make that argument and some of the state courts have certainly suggested that under state law, no easement by necessity can be -- yes, sir.","start":316.345,"stop":324.268,"duration":7.92}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":324.268,"stop":324.721,"duration":0.45},{"text":"You're claiming a reservation.","start":324.721,"stop":326.335,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":326.335,"stop":326.891,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And so --","start":326.891,"stop":327.103,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"And we are --","start":327.103,"stop":327.787,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And the --","start":327.787,"stop":327.842,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- using that --","start":327.842,"stop":329.626,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"To follow up my Brother Rehnquist question, now are we hearing the area of real property law or we are -- are we in the area of simple legislative construction?","start":329.626,"stop":345.154,"duration":15.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"We believe that this is primarily a question of legislative construction.","start":345.154,"stop":348.554,"duration":3.4},{"text":"What we think in trying to interpret what it was that Congress was doing that not only may Congress intent be judged by what its assumptions were about property law but also that there is an underlying logic to the common law dealing with easements by necessity which is that a grantor must have intended to reserve a right to make use of the property that he retained that that's manifest in the pattern of his grant.","start":348.554,"stop":373.351,"duration":24.8},{"text":"And that is what we really rely upon --","start":373.351,"stop":374.403,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Do it also follows that in the -- that the grant to the railroad was also a grant of an easement over the retained property of the Government, wouldn't it?","start":374.403,"stop":383.518,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we think not.","start":383.518,"stop":384.309,"duration":0.79},{"text":"And again, by looking to the circumstances of --","start":384.309,"stop":387.295,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The same circumstances applied, each one is land lock so to speak, isn't it?","start":387.295,"stop":390.943,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's not quite true in the sense that for many, many years of -- before the land grants were made the Federal Government had developed a well-established policy of allowing locations of roadways, all across the public domain.","start":390.943,"stop":405.96,"duration":15.02}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":405.96,"stop":406.159,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, that was not established by statute until 1866.","start":406.159,"stop":409.583,"duration":3.42},{"text":"But this Court has clearly in the Alameda County case which we cite in our brief.","start":409.583,"stop":414.084,"duration":4.5},{"text":"Interpreted that 1866 Act as con -- as a recognition of a preexisting right that was broader then, really.","start":414.084,"stop":423.564,"duration":9.48},{"text":"Anything that would be needed to gain access to the checkerboard land grants, any is different in kind from simple right of access back and forth from one checker to another.","start":423.564,"stop":434.033,"duration":10.47},{"text":"So we think that the context of the most logical assumption is that Congress knew that it had a policy of allowing runways to be located across the public domain.","start":434.033,"stop":444.994,"duration":10.96},{"text":"Otherwise, they never could have been settled anywhere.","start":444.994,"stop":447.66,"duration":2.67},{"text":"And that provides one part of the context with this Act but the other part of the context is that when it left a 100 million acres land lot in a checkerboard fashion that it must have been intended to reserve a legal right to get in and out, ingress and egress for those sections.","start":447.66,"stop":465.239,"duration":17.58},{"text":"Not a right dependent upon the fact that no one would challenge them.","start":465.239,"stop":469.78,"duration":4.54},{"text":"It didn't intend that all federal officers, agents and grantee should be trespassers who could be thrown off.","start":469.78,"stop":475.751,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Miss Beale, to go back to the Alameda County and the custom that was established, would the roads established person that customer that drives survive a patent of the Government sections to a landowner?","start":475.751,"stop":489.834,"duration":14.08}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":489.834,"stop":490.41,"duration":0.58},{"text":"The patents were taken subject to the runways that were established?","start":490.41,"stop":494.914,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"How about --","start":494.914,"stop":494.937,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I think there's a good body of case law to that effect --","start":494.937,"stop":497.062,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"How about roadways that weren't actually established?","start":497.062,"stop":500.305,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean, if no roadway --","start":500.305,"stop":501.373,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":501.373,"stop":501.424,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- had ever been established?","start":501.424,"stop":502.819,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"By the time of the patent.","start":502.819,"stop":505.543,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":505.543,"stop":506.265,"duration":0.72},{"text":"The custom that was established pursuant or that was recognized in that statute would not have affected those.","start":506.265,"stop":512.043,"duration":5.78},{"text":"They would be like any other private property and presumably one would go to -- through another area if the owner at that point took his land and had built an improvement or whatever.","start":512.043,"stop":523.642,"duration":11.6}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well since 1862, countless roads have been constructed through these areas, have they by state and local governments by the power of eminent domain?","start":523.642,"stop":533.998,"duration":10.36}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, certainly the power of eminent domain had been used of variety of different methods were used to locate these roads.","start":533.998,"stop":540.649,"duration":6.65},{"text":"Pursuant to the statute that I just described, the state followed varying methods.","start":540.649,"stop":545.849,"duration":5.2},{"text":"One of the states at least and perhaps others passed the statute that dedicated all of the section lines as public roads, so that as settlers came in, those were recognized as public roads.","start":545.849,"stop":558.205,"duration":12.36},{"text":"Other states relied more upon prescription in some place counties, territorial governments, set up roads in -- and a variety of methods were used to locate those roads.","start":558.205,"stop":567.18,"duration":8.97}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But in any event in the last 116 years, many, many new roads had been constructed through these areas, haven't they?","start":567.18,"stop":575.237,"duration":8.06}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":575.237,"stop":576.407,"duration":1.17},{"text":"And we --","start":576.407,"stop":577.352,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Often -- often as through the exercise of eminent domain by -- by state and local governments, isn't that true?","start":577.352,"stop":583.883,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- first of all, I'd like to be clear on when we're saying these areas.","start":583.883,"stop":587.633,"duration":3.75},{"text":"I mean the areas where the checkerboard grants were located.","start":587.633,"stop":589.7,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, the general areas where we have the checkerboard system as a the result of the 1862 statute.","start":589.7,"stop":593.939,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, and that would include both the land granted to the railroads --","start":593.939,"stop":596.569,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":596.569,"stop":597.1,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as well as to the --","start":597.1,"stop":597.691,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":597.691,"stop":597.821,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to the -- the public and I guess what I -- my clearest answer would be that the record here is not precise as to what was done in each locality.","start":597.821,"stop":607.737,"duration":9.92},{"text":"And as to who owned the land when a particular road was located either on land granted to the railroad, land granted to the United States, there were some grant to a private party.","start":607.737,"stop":618.078,"duration":10.34},{"text":"Whether the land was owned by the Federal Government and the county decided more than an easement, decided more to look than to locate a road.","start":618.078,"stop":624.535,"duration":6.46},{"text":"In any event, the current authority for locating easements or whatever cost fairly and just as we've mention to the 1976 statute adopted by Congress' party to federal land policy in Management Act.","start":624.535,"stop":639.908,"duration":15.37},{"text":"And if a private owner of a railroad land that was originally patented to the railroad needed to locate an easement to get in and out of his checker.","start":639.908,"stop":652.142,"duration":12.23},{"text":"Now, that's not the case here because of course the Leo Sheep Company and Palm Livestock Company have tailored grazing it permit and they do not require -- there having a problem of access.","start":652.142,"stop":662.557,"duration":10.41},{"text":"But if they did, they could apply to the Secretary of Interior and get an easement in and out, if need be.","start":662.557,"stop":668.59,"duration":6.03},{"text":"So there is a mechanism and the particular statute passing 1866 is no longer enforced.","start":668.59,"stop":674.278,"duration":5.69},{"text":"But -- but there is a mechanism and I would emphasize to the Court that we did not go into in great length the reasons why believe that no reciprocal easement was created across the federal lands for one reason because it is so clear that in this particular case, no such easement was required or claimed.","start":674.278,"stop":694.348,"duration":20.07},{"text":"And indeed we think that that was as it -- this is a general matter quite true that the federal statutory provisions, the policies, the new provision are quite adequate and have been quite adequate to ensure that the grantee over the railroad have had access, and that's really not a problem.","start":694.348,"stop":710.368,"duration":16.02}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course 116 years to avoid this basic question hand arisen before in a 116 years and it occurred to me the reason is that they -- as a practical matter doesn't often arise because there are roads through this area.","start":710.368,"stop":723.098,"duration":12.73},{"text":"There is access by public roadway.","start":723.098,"stop":725.77,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, certainly now there're many roadways.","start":725.77,"stop":727.419,"duration":1.65},{"text":"We have cited in our brief some of the early cases which do in fact recognize the theory that we put forth here that there is an implied reservation so that there -- the grantees of the United States and federal agents and so forth can go in and out.","start":727.419,"stop":743.35,"duration":15.93},{"text":"That's another answer to why this wasn't a problem.","start":743.35,"stop":747.436,"duration":4.09},{"text":"And we should emphasize that the right that we claim here is in essence only when to have important applications in areas like this.","start":747.436,"stop":755.666,"duration":8.23},{"text":"Where -- where there are not a pattern of roadways already built up.","start":755.666,"stop":759.359,"duration":3.69},{"text":"We claim only the necessary access in and out, ingress and egress and in developed areas, that's simply not a problem.","start":759.359,"stop":767.66,"duration":8.3}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But not for the Government, for the public.","start":767.66,"stop":770.092,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, for governmental purposes which would include --","start":770.092,"stop":773.512,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That this is by the public to this late --","start":773.512,"stop":776.289,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly would include that and it would also --","start":776.289,"stop":777.15,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a public roadway, isn't it?","start":777.15,"stop":778.943,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- yes, it is.","start":778.943,"stop":779.824,"duration":0.88},{"text":"It is a one lane --","start":779.824,"stop":780.373,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not for just -- to federal use?","start":780.373,"stop":782.553,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- perhaps, it is not absence that it's limited to the use of federal officers and agents.","start":782.553,"stop":789.91,"duration":7.36},{"text":"But it's a --","start":789.91,"stop":790.385,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not, is it?","start":790.385,"stop":790.611,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- federally built -- that's correct.","start":790.611,"stop":791.999,"duration":1.39},{"text":"It's a federally constructed reservoir and it's a federally used in that sense.","start":791.999,"stop":796.64,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"This is accessed by -- for the general public?","start":796.64,"stop":799.61,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":799.61,"stop":799.976,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"To this recreational area?","start":799.976,"stop":801.373,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":801.373,"stop":801.965,"duration":0.59},{"text":"It's a one lane to --","start":801.965,"stop":802.566,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"This is generally -- ordinarily be served by a public road.","start":802.566,"stop":807.5,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, in that sense.","start":807.5,"stop":810.553,"duration":3.05},{"text":"So I would emphasize as I say that the right that we claim here is a narrow one that we find to be implicit in the pattern of the grants and not a common law easement by necessity.","start":810.553,"stop":823.515,"duration":12.96},{"text":"And we think really the burden of the petitioner's argument is to establish that there is another reasonable alternative.","start":823.515,"stop":829.813,"duration":6.3},{"text":"Congress must have intended that there could be used made of these retained 100 million acres.","start":829.813,"stop":837.606,"duration":7.79},{"text":"And the question is really whether there is any reasonable alternative to the construction that we've put for it.","start":837.606,"stop":843.245,"duration":5.64},{"text":"I've already suggested that we find -- that we believe the use of eminent domain to secure a right of access to each of these sections.","start":843.245,"stop":851.852,"duration":8.61},{"text":"Would've been totally unworkable and moreover, there's no suggestion and its clear from the history that that method was not used.","start":851.852,"stop":860.907,"duration":9.06},{"text":"And we think likewise the suggestion that Congress provided only that the settlers should work it out among themselves that perhaps stay in local laws if eminent domain would be used.","start":860.907,"stop":872.766,"duration":11.86},{"text":"That perhaps people would not object to the passage of Government settlers and so forth is really not one that can be implied as what Congress intended.","start":872.766,"stop":884.363,"duration":11.6},{"text":"The grants here were made to several large railroad corporations --","start":884.363,"stop":888.995,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mrs. Beale --","start":888.995,"stop":889.236,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and.","start":889.236,"stop":889.953,"duration":0.72},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":889.953,"stop":890.099,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- may I interrupt just a minute.","start":890.099,"stop":891.103,"duration":1},{"text":"Who would determine the location of these reserved rights of way?","start":891.103,"stop":895.71,"duration":4.61},{"text":"Specifically, where would they go and who would decide it?","start":895.71,"stop":899.662,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we think the principle that would be applied here is the general property law principle that applies to other kinds of easements by implication where there is no instrument that fixes the location and the general rule which we think is applicable here.","start":899.662,"stop":914.769,"duration":15.11},{"text":"Is that they must be located in a manner that provides a minimal intrusion on the land that the easement crosses.","start":914.769,"stop":922.267,"duration":7.5},{"text":"We think in many cases asked here, the location would be across the corner.","start":922.267,"stop":926.996,"duration":4.73},{"text":"In the first instance, there would be an attempt to reach agreement between the two parties, the Government or the Government's grantee and the grantee of the railroad.","start":926.996,"stop":938.564,"duration":11.57},{"text":"And if that were not possible, which was the case here, the government or its grantee would have a choice of locating the easement where it was least intrusive.","start":938.564,"stop":951.404,"duration":12.84},{"text":"So that in this case it was almost precisely on the corners except in one case there was a gate of some sort, a little down from the corner.","start":951.404,"stop":959.686,"duration":8.28},{"text":"And the Government used that --","start":959.686,"stop":961.403,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you see if there was -- if there were no agreement that the Government would then determine where it should be located.","start":961.403,"stop":966.764,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":966.764,"stop":966.837,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Why would you go to court?","start":966.837,"stop":967.245,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly it would be subject to --","start":967.245,"stop":969.711,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Litigation?","start":969.711,"stop":969.752,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- either judicial proceedings --","start":969.752,"stop":970.992,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":970.992,"stop":971.048,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to determine whether the Government's choice was reasonable.","start":971.048,"stop":973.461,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":973.461,"stop":973.576,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"But in the first instance, the Government would need to try to satisfy the grantor, and if the grantor would not -- of the railroad.","start":973.576,"stop":980.118,"duration":6.54},{"text":"If the grantor of the railroad would not agree and would not say where he wanted it and the Government would have to try and determine what would be reasonable.","start":980.118,"stop":987.883,"duration":7.76},{"text":"And I suppose either in this case -- either of two methods could be used.","start":987.883,"stop":991.741,"duration":3.86},{"text":"In this case, we located it where we felt it certainly was the least intrusive spot and the grantor brought an action against us, the railroad's grantor.","start":991.741,"stop":1002.166,"duration":10.43},{"text":"I suppose we could also perhaps bring a suit to determine a declaratory judgment where it should be located.","start":1002.166,"stop":1007.927,"duration":5.76}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And this is a permanent road, the owner would never had anymore use of that corner?","start":1007.927,"stop":1014.146,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in this particular case for example.","start":1014.146,"stop":1016.984,"duration":2.84},{"text":"It's a dirt road, I suppose if the owner needed to have it moved that might to make use of his property.","start":1016.984,"stop":1022.976,"duration":5.99},{"text":"There might be some negotiation.","start":1022.976,"stop":1024.712,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But while the road --","start":1024.712,"stop":1024.833,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"All we have is the right of access.","start":1024.833,"stop":1026.487,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But while the Federal Government was using it and the public was using it, and he couldn't use it?","start":1026.487,"stop":1030.969,"duration":4.48}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1030.969,"stop":1031.738,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Rather, the sheep could've used it?","start":1031.738,"stop":1033.973,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"I think its cattle in this case despite the name of the company but --","start":1033.973,"stop":1036.251,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, sheep, cattle, bulldogs, whatever it is --","start":1036.251,"stop":1038.848,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, right.","start":1038.848,"stop":1039.912,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"They couldn't use it.","start":1039.912,"stop":1041.032,"duration":1.12},{"text":"The land is gone so far as the private owner is concerned.","start":1041.032,"stop":1045.015,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1045.015,"stop":1045.55,"duration":0.53},{"text":"In the sense that he couldn't stop the public --","start":1045.55,"stop":1046.954,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"So to that extent --","start":1046.954,"stop":1047.563,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Does he pay taxes on it?","start":1047.563,"stop":1051.952,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"I think less the value of the easement.","start":1051.952,"stop":1055.047,"duration":3.1},{"text":"His taxes would be reduced in the sense that his property would be valued by -- would be less than the value of the -- you know, subtract the value of the easement.","start":1055.047,"stop":1062.008,"duration":6.96}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Normally in -- this is more than just an easement if -- as we agree as this for the -- for public, use as a public road.","start":1062.008,"stop":1072.506,"duration":10.5},{"text":"It's more than an easement for just to access, ingress and egress over a piece of property which the fee title owner retains title to as suggested by my Brother Marshall.","start":1072.506,"stop":1083.794,"duration":11.29},{"text":"This is a -- a road generally is -- the title goes to the governmental body that owns and operates the road?","start":1083.794,"stop":1090.34,"duration":6.55}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not certain with the most usual --","start":1090.34,"stop":1092.88,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, in other words, there couldn't be grazing or anything else on this road, if it's a road.","start":1092.88,"stop":1096.313,"duration":3.43},{"text":"And if you're right, it's more than just an easement of once a day or once a week, the -- an adjacent owner going over it?","start":1096.313,"stop":1103.294,"duration":6.98}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think its equally in the case of -- lets go get to our paradigm case of the private grantor who would perhaps make a grant of this same size, a piece of property to adjacent pieces, a need to reserve a right of access.","start":1103.294,"stop":1120.142,"duration":16.85},{"text":"In some case --","start":1120.142,"stop":1120.165,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Cross easements --","start":1120.165,"stop":1121.281,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon me?","start":1121.281,"stop":1121.936,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You're talking about cross easements of adjacent landowners?","start":1121.936,"stop":1124.849,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you imagine the donut shape which is always the law book example --","start":1124.849,"stop":1128.344,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1128.344,"stop":1128.697,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the grantor reserves the little piece of the donut in the center.","start":1128.697,"stop":1130.812,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1130.812,"stop":1131.783,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"And we refer to his having reserved an easement even though, it maybe necessary in some case to have a dirt road such as this.","start":1131.783,"stop":1140.5,"duration":8.72},{"text":"He may have -- he may subdivide that and put --","start":1140.5,"stop":1141.11,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's not a public road?","start":1141.11,"stop":1142.914,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry?","start":1142.914,"stop":1143.017,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The easement belongs to the fee title owner of the center of the donut --","start":1143.017,"stop":1149.008,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"The easement belongs --","start":1149.008,"stop":1149.398,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- for his use.","start":1149.398,"stop":1150.638,"duration":1.24},{"text":"It's not for the use of the public.","start":1150.638,"stop":1152.487,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's for the uses that he can offer it --","start":1152.487,"stop":1154.325,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"His use including his visitors.","start":1154.325,"stop":1157.217,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- well, that's right and I guess I would say that are used (Inaudible) include the visitors to our reservoir.","start":1157.217,"stop":1162.791,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mrs. Beale, one more question.","start":1162.791,"stop":1164.956,"duration":2.16},{"text":"For all practical purposes insofar as the owner of this land is concerned.","start":1164.956,"stop":1174.652,"duration":9.7},{"text":"If you succeed here and use this corner of his land, what is the difference so far as he is concerned and his rights by taking it this way or taking it by eminent domain outside the money?","start":1174.652,"stop":1202.163,"duration":27.51}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that the best answer to that is, if there is a system of public loads -- roads later located in this area our right of access would no longer be enforceable.","start":1202.163,"stop":1214.501,"duration":12.34},{"text":"In other words, if we can get in and out of our lands otherwise as soon as an area becomes built up --","start":1214.501,"stop":1219.078,"duration":4.58}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you take --","start":1219.078,"stop":1219.212,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- we no longer have a right --","start":1219.212,"stop":1220.508,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would you take the road up and move it?","start":1220.508,"stop":1223.181,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in this case and perhaps this is the easiest example of all.","start":1223.181,"stop":1226.732,"duration":3.55},{"text":"All we did was come in and blade-off the grass to provide a track to go in and out.","start":1226.732,"stop":1231.576,"duration":4.84},{"text":"Now in other cases perhaps it would be necessary for us to put on gravel or whatever and then take it up if we no longer needed that for right of access.","start":1231.576,"stop":1239.347,"duration":7.77},{"text":"But the -- and this goes back to the point that Mr. Justice Stewart was making also that the railroad grantee does retain the title to that land.","start":1239.347,"stop":1248.746,"duration":9.4},{"text":"And if are easement or right of access or way of access in and out is no longer necessary for us to use then we no longer have a right.","start":1248.746,"stop":1259.331,"duration":10.58},{"text":"We no longer have enforceable right and that is an important difference than what would happen in the case of eminent domain where we would take full permanent title to that land.","start":1259.331,"stop":1269.05,"duration":9.72}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's my -- that was going to be my question.","start":1269.05,"stop":1271.229,"duration":2.18},{"text":"Ordinarily, when the Federal Government wants to build a public road and proceeds to acquire the property by condemnation proceedings does it try to acquire just and easement or does it try to acquire the fee?","start":1271.229,"stop":1285.139,"duration":13.91}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Martz may have some comment on this.","start":1285.139,"stop":1288.209,"duration":3.07},{"text":"It's my understanding, very often we acquire only in easement.","start":1288.209,"stop":1291.55,"duration":3.34},{"text":"Now, that may not be the case in the case of a eight-lane superhighway.","start":1291.55,"stop":1295.089,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1295.089,"stop":1295.169,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Perhaps when the project is so large, a fee title is taken but in many cases only an easement is taken.","start":1295.169,"stop":1302.475,"duration":7.31},{"text":"And I'm not certain where the dividing line is.","start":1302.475,"stop":1304.873,"duration":2.4},{"text":"There maybe discretion.","start":1304.873,"stop":1306.746,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Miss --","start":1306.746,"stop":1306.814,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Mrs. Beale, I was going to ask you about the eight-lanes superhighway as Justice Stewart has suggested, you can have anything from a -- of a footpath to a swimming hole perhaps to the eight-lane superhighway.","start":1306.814,"stop":1321.107,"duration":14.29},{"text":"If there's no definition of the reservation for which you argue, would it be permissible under your theory of the case if -- for the Government to say, what we really need is the superhighway?","start":1321.107,"stop":1332.449,"duration":11.34}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1332.449,"stop":1333.137,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Why -- why not?","start":1333.137,"stop":1334.364,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"We believe that all that was implicitly reserved here is a reasonable right of ingress and egress to make use of these properties.","start":1334.364,"stop":1342.641,"duration":8.28},{"text":"Now, we -- certainly the problem is more difficult here than if the grants had spelled out by metes and bounds or whatever, what that would entail?","start":1342.641,"stop":1351.669,"duration":9.03},{"text":"But there's a whole body of common law which has developed in terms of or to meet the problem of trying to define what is reserved when there's an implied easement.","start":1351.669,"stop":1361.487,"duration":9.82},{"text":"And we think that that body of law would be looked to here to determine the extent.","start":1361.487,"stop":1366.427,"duration":4.94},{"text":"And in essence, what we're saying is what Congress could have reasonably foreseen as a need to get in and out to make use of those sections would govern.","start":1366.427,"stop":1374.82,"duration":8.39},{"text":"Certainly what we have here I think is within what Congress would have intended.","start":1374.82,"stop":1379.384,"duration":4.56},{"text":"Congress believed that these sections as Mr. Martz described yesterday would in fact that retained Government sections would be subject to homesteading and development.","start":1379.384,"stop":1388.614,"duration":9.23},{"text":"Congress thought that putting the railroads out to the west would bring people from the east, allow them to settle and develop that land.","start":1388.614,"stop":1394.614,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mrs. Beale, then you would measure reasonable as of 1862 rather than as of today, isn't it right?","start":1394.614,"stop":1399.677,"duration":5.06}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, only in the sense of what Congress could have comprehended and Congress did clearly comprehend development of those sections.","start":1399.677,"stop":1407.911,"duration":8.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1407.911,"stop":1407.92,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"If something perhaps like the process that the Court goes through in the case of implied water reservations where the notion is that at the time the conveyance for the grantor whatever was made or the reservation was made.","start":1407.92,"stop":1422.799,"duration":14.88},{"text":"What Congress foresaw is the present and the foreseeable future needs is the guide.","start":1422.799,"stop":1428.23,"duration":5.43},{"text":"And that is the same guide that's used in the case of a private grantor and we would say clearly the roadway here is within that contemplation.","start":1428.23,"stop":1439.297,"duration":11.07}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would your position be the same assuming that within two or three years after the transfer to the railroad, the Government had sold all of the Section 1622 and 14 to a private owner.","start":1439.297,"stop":1454.491,"duration":15.19},{"text":"Would that private owner have precisely the same claim the Government is now asserting?","start":1454.491,"stop":1458.809,"duration":4.32},{"text":"And then the private owner developed the reservoir?","start":1458.809,"stop":1463.612,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm -- it's not clear to me why there would be any difference.","start":1463.612,"stop":1466.024,"duration":2.41},{"text":"We do think that the right that Congress reserved was for the benefit of those pieces of -- parcels of land so that they could be used.","start":1466.024,"stop":1472.464,"duration":6.44},{"text":"In an instance, the benefit would be conveyed with the parcels of land.","start":1472.464,"stop":1477.02,"duration":4.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words --","start":1477.02,"stop":1477.239,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, we do no good if we only had the right to use it.","start":1477.239,"stop":1479.957,"duration":2.72},{"text":"But as soon as we conveyed it to the settlers that we expect to --","start":1479.957,"stop":1481.659,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't relied at all on the fact that it is the United States Government were to solve or anything like that?","start":1481.659,"stop":1486.407,"duration":4.75},{"text":"It would be --","start":1486.407,"stop":1486.513,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"No, not in that sense, no.","start":1486.513,"stop":1486.884,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it was precisely the same claim could be made by an assignee if the Government sent this?","start":1486.884,"stop":1491.673,"duration":4.79}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1491.673,"stop":1492.074,"duration":0.4},{"text":"And -- and we think that is so precisely because of our understanding of what Congress was trying to do here which was to grant the odd-numbered sections to the railroads to encourage them to build this rail line, keeping these retained sections knowing that there would be enhancing value that they would be available for settlement and planning to sell those off at double the normal price recouping the investment that it had made to the railroad and allowing settlement to progress out west.","start":1492.074,"stop":1521.883,"duration":29.81},{"text":"And only by reserving the right to get in and out in for its grantees and the settlers and so forth to have a right to grin -- to get in and out of those sections could that plan really have been accomplished.","start":1521.883,"stop":1533.885,"duration":12},{"text":"And that's the problem of course with the petitioners' argument.","start":1533.885,"stop":1537.106,"duration":3.22},{"text":"Even if Congress has assumed that in many cases no one would have objected, its planned for the development of the rail lines and the settlement of these sections was dependent upon a right of these settlers to get in and make use of this land that would not be subject to veto power in essence by several large railroad corporations who owned the sections completely surrounding each one of the retained public sections.","start":1537.106,"stop":1560.942,"duration":23.84}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I just -- I want to make sure I didn't misunderstand something, earlier you said, you do not take the position however that the railroad had a corresponding right as against the reserved lands?","start":1560.942,"stop":1571.459,"duration":10.52}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct and we believe that is so because again, look in --","start":1571.459,"stop":1573.559,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But why would they -- they were going to sell to people who would be neighbors.","start":1573.559,"stop":1576.388,"duration":2.83},{"text":"Why would that be different?","start":1576.388,"stop":1577.32,"duration":0.93},{"text":"I just -- I need some help on that?","start":1577.32,"stop":1578.706,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, because when the railroads, settlers, grantees, whatever came in.","start":1578.706,"stop":1583.112,"duration":4.41},{"text":"They had the right under the 1866 Act to locate their roads across the public domain.","start":1583.112,"stop":1589.281,"duration":6.17},{"text":"And we believe that was the mechanism that was used.","start":1589.281,"stop":1592.059,"duration":2.78},{"text":"Now, we don't disagree for moment that by enlarge most of these problems were worked out by agreement among the parties because everyone needed to get in and out but in the sense of a necessity for reserving a legal right of access.","start":1592.059,"stop":1606.927,"duration":14.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry, I must -- I'm -- perhaps not grasping the full period.","start":1606.927,"stop":1610.115,"duration":3.19},{"text":"You say the grantees from the railroad had a right to locate roads over the reserved public lands.","start":1610.115,"stop":1617.076,"duration":6.96},{"text":"But what if --","start":1617.076,"stop":1617.386,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Under --","start":1617.386,"stop":1617.581,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the public lands had been sold in the meantime?","start":1617.581,"stop":1619.656,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1619.656,"stop":1620.526,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in essence at some point, one gets back to the same problem that it took place under the Homestead Acts and under the other location of the Preemption Acts and so forth which is that some grantee may have wanted to locate a road across someone else's --","start":1620.526,"stop":1636.842,"duration":16.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, am I correct -- let me just stick with this to be sure I understand.","start":1636.842,"stop":1639.852,"duration":3.01},{"text":"Am I correct in assuming that at least it was theoretically possible, if all the land was sold that the people in the odd-numbered sections would not have the right you say the people in the even-numbered sections would have?","start":1639.852,"stop":1651.146,"duration":11.29}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1651.146,"stop":1652.135,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1652.135,"stop":1652.513,"duration":0.38},{"text":"I said, had all --","start":1652.513,"stop":1653.759,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And you said the --","start":1653.759,"stop":1653.91,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Happened at one cell through -- suddenly without any location --","start":1653.91,"stop":1656.4,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it reasonable that Congress so intended?","start":1656.4,"stop":1659.33,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we believe not only that it is reasonable that the plan shows that and that what has happened in the intervening years makes that clear too.","start":1659.33,"stop":1668.635,"duration":9.31},{"text":"There -- virtually no instances of the railroad grantees who in fact had the problem that you described.","start":1668.635,"stop":1675.051,"duration":6.42},{"text":"The 1866 Act was used extensively.","start":1675.051,"stop":1678.808,"duration":3.76},{"text":"The Title V provisions are used now and the problem that we have that we do see occasionally cropping up is the railroads and their grantees blocking access.","start":1678.808,"stop":1689.713,"duration":10.9},{"text":"One of the entrances of course to this is that the only large block conveyance was to the railroads.","start":1689.713,"stop":1695.77,"duration":6.06},{"text":"The only single party who could have blocked access is in any one area is the railroad who received all of these grants.","start":1695.77,"stop":1703.876,"duration":8.11},{"text":"In the case of grants of -- to small party's homestead --","start":1703.876,"stop":1706.507,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But they received but they understanding and they would resell, wasn't it, that part of the idea?","start":1706.507,"stop":1711.066,"duration":4.56}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"The railroads received the land --","start":1711.066,"stop":1713.18,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"On the understanding it would be financing and therefore, they were expected to resell, I know that they --","start":1713.18,"stop":1717.311,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"They were --","start":1717.311,"stop":1717.377,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"How do they sell it or else it would be subject to a homestead in your --","start":1717.377,"stop":1719.689,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"They had to sell or dispose --","start":1719.689,"stop":1721.444,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and they --","start":1721.444,"stop":1721.902,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- which meant -- and there was no requirement that the railroad lands be sold off to small landowners.","start":1721.902,"stop":1728.875,"duration":6.97},{"text":"In fact, that didn't happen in many areas.","start":1728.875,"stop":1730.682,"duration":1.81},{"text":"The Government lands which are to be disposed off in a -- essentially 160-acre parcels.","start":1730.682,"stop":1735.591,"duration":4.91},{"text":"Single little parties scattered all over the west.","start":1735.591,"stop":1739.528,"duration":3.94},{"text":"The only large block prints, the only party who could've frustrated the development of a whole area was the railroad who received --","start":1739.528,"stop":1747.339,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that's true, but they were expected to develop the land and thereby enhanced the value of the retained Government lands.","start":1747.339,"stop":1752.532,"duration":5.19}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's --","start":1752.532,"stop":1752.975,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But somehow they (Voice Overlap) --","start":1752.975,"stop":1753.599,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"-- why in the sense that the -- and it's perhaps maybe a little more complicated than that in the sense that the Platte case recognized that all the railroads had to do was to make some use of this land to finance the construction of the railroads within a certain point after the railroads were constructed.","start":1753.599,"stop":1773.716,"duration":20.12},{"text":"They were able to and they did in many cases convey largely into holdings to a subsidiary to a mortgagor and that party just as much as the railroad could have blocked the development and settlement of the Government sections.","start":1773.716,"stop":1788.652,"duration":14.94},{"text":"No grantee of the Government would have had that kind of power.","start":1788.652,"stop":1791.869,"duration":3.22},{"text":"It wasn't possible for any single grantee of the Government in these 160-acre parcels to frustrate the development of the land granted to the railroad and it didn't happen.","start":1791.869,"stop":1803.829,"duration":11.96},{"text":"And I would emphasize again that we did not develop all of the reasons in our briefs.","start":1803.829,"stop":1810.082,"duration":6.25},{"text":"Why we moved -- we -- that there is no retained or there was no grant of an easement across the Government lands because that question is not in the case.","start":1810.082,"stop":1818.963,"duration":8.88},{"text":"That the part -- the petitioners here have the Taylor Grazing Act permits and they used all of our lands whereas Mr. Justice Blackmun pointed out yesterday, what we want to do is use a corner of their lands.","start":1818.963,"stop":1831.029,"duration":12.07},{"text":"I see my time is up.","start":1831.029,"stop":1832.598,"duration":1.57},{"text":"Unless there are further --","start":1832.598,"stop":1833.577,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mrs. Beale, I do have one further question.","start":1833.577,"stop":1836.037,"duration":2.46},{"text":"Your answers to the questions posed by some of my colleagues on the opposite side of the bench indicate that the parties would be entitled to litigate in Court over the reasonableness of the Government -- of the easement which the Government designated across the property.","start":1836.037,"stop":1855.336,"duration":19.3},{"text":"Doesn't that undercut to a certain extent your original argument that Congress couldn't have intended a system whereby Congress had to go -- the Government had to go and then condemn this by eminent domain because the Courts just couldn't have handled it?","start":1855.336,"stop":1870.831,"duration":15.49}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I guess that I would say, not in the sense that in most cases particularly before the land was developed to any great extent.","start":1870.831,"stop":1878.627,"duration":7.8},{"text":"The obvious reasonable place would be the corner and there would be no point to the private grantee of the railroad going to Court to challenge that.","start":1878.627,"stop":1886.836,"duration":8.21},{"text":"He'd get nothing out of it.","start":1886.836,"stop":1887.763,"duration":0.93},{"text":"That would clearly be the least intrusive.","start":1887.763,"stop":1889.125,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"That's doing eminent domain to though, isn't it?","start":1889.125,"stop":1891.342,"duration":2.22},{"text":"I mean, the intent -- many eminent domain cases, the private owner welcomes the Government putting in a road and that simply agrees not to seek any condemnation not -- the expenses or value in exchange for the value to him of the road?","start":1891.342,"stop":1908.133,"duration":16.79}]},{"speakerName":"Sara Sun Beale","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that maybe true and I guess our point is really that.","start":1908.133,"stop":1912.302,"duration":4.17},{"text":"If Congress had thought that no one could enter these sections except as trespassers until it went out section by section and determined.","start":1912.302,"stop":1920.771,"duration":8.47},{"text":"Did it have to bring an eminent domain proceeding and to bring those in cases where that was necessary?","start":1920.771,"stop":1925.848,"duration":5.08},{"text":"That would be substantially more difficult process than what we suggest happened which is that there was a right to locate upon what appeared to be or to cross -- what appeared to be at the reasonable and least intrusive spot.","start":1925.848,"stop":1939.491,"duration":13.64},{"text":"And if it --if a dispute developed, then the parties would try and work it out.","start":1939.491,"stop":1943.654,"duration":4.16},{"text":"And if not, the landowner could go to Court and say, \"Wait a minute, you should use my gate down here and not go across the corner\", or \"Wait a minute, I want to locate a house on the corner and you should go further down\", and that is different.","start":1943.654,"stop":1955.813,"duration":12.16},{"text":"If only those disputed cases are subject to litigation, we would think.","start":1955.813,"stop":1963.238,"duration":7.42},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1963.238,"stop":1963.791,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":1963.791,"stop":1964.407,"duration":0.62},{"text":"Mr. Martz, do you have anything further?","start":1964.407,"stop":1969.174,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":1969.174,"stop":1972.899,"duration":3.72},{"text":"I'd like to make a couple of comments and then see if the Court has any questions with me.","start":1972.899,"stop":1978.458,"duration":5.56},{"text":"I thought that the counsel's analysis of the relationship between the odd and even-numbered sections provided an answer to a question Mr. Justice Blackmun put to me yesterday which is really what at stake in this controversy.","start":1978.458,"stop":1999.697,"duration":21.24},{"text":"Counsel says that the -- if the successors and enters to the odd-numbered sections, one access across the alternate even-numbered sections if still in public ownership they may seek a permit from the Secretary of Interior.","start":1999.697,"stop":2018.554,"duration":18.86},{"text":"There's nothing in the law that says that permit has to be granted or that it would be granted free of terms and conditions and restrictions.","start":2018.554,"stop":2026.451,"duration":7.9},{"text":"If those lands have passed a private ownership by homesteading, counsel had made it very clear that the homestead had took a free title without any encumbrance upon if for the benefit of the alternate odd-numbered sections.","start":2026.451,"stop":2041.199,"duration":14.75},{"text":"But if the United States either for access to the alternate even-numbered sections or for public access to a development such as Seminoe Reservoir wants to use the private lands of successors and enters of the railroad they can take that road without compensation, determine the size of the burden where the road will be located with the right in the landowner to either negotiate for some alternative.","start":2041.199,"stop":2076.583,"duration":35.38},{"text":"Or to go to Court and seek a determination that the easement is excessive.","start":2076.583,"stop":2089.938,"duration":13.36},{"text":"The landowner may have paid taxes upon the land subject to the taking of a road for an easement.","start":2089.938,"stop":2099.135,"duration":9.2},{"text":"I think if the Court would look at United States against Ridge -- Ringe in the Southern District of California cited on page 19 of our brief.","start":2099.135,"stop":2112.547,"duration":13.41},{"text":"We see the burden that's posed -- that's put on the ranching landowner of the Government exercising these rights of driving roadways or highways willy-nilly across ranch lands, breaking it up into parcels and destroying the utility of the land, now in the hands of purchasers for value based upon clear patents and a clear record title by examination.","start":2112.547,"stop":2143.753,"duration":31.21},{"text":"If the Government has to go by con -- the condemnation route, it will have to pay not just for the small bits of land on corner crossings but it must -- going to have to address the impairment of value to the residual lands caused by the opening of unfenced public access routes across consolidated ranch areas.","start":2143.753,"stop":2179.515,"duration":35.76},{"text":"This Court has said many times as cited on page 24 of petitioner's brief that a construction that others title securities should be limited to cases where there is a compelling need and that litigation should be avoided as a consequence of a construction.","start":2179.515,"stop":2210.64,"duration":31.13},{"text":"Here we have a case where we have had a uniformed administrative construction for a 100 and now 16 years.","start":2210.64,"stop":2221.219,"duration":10.58},{"text":"It's apparent that if the Court of Appeals decision is sustained, we're going to impose an encumbrance upon some a 131,000 acres that had been patented under language like Section 3 in this and other Acts.","start":2221.219,"stop":2241.684,"duration":20.47},{"text":"It's not illogically that we're also going to cloud a 100 million acres of title in these reserved even-numbered sections.","start":2241.684,"stop":2251.117,"duration":9.43},{"text":"And as -- the Government has pointed out in our argument, we're going to have litigation over the size and burden of these rights of way.","start":2251.117,"stop":2260.143,"duration":9.03}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"That might be more complex than the kind of litigation we traditionally have over a condemnation, would it not?","start":2260.143,"stop":2266.978,"duration":6.84}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Much more so particularly when the values that counsel describes -- I'm sorry Your Honor.","start":2266.978,"stop":2273.575,"duration":6.6}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Go ahead.","start":2273.575,"stop":2274.648,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"We shall I finish?","start":2274.648,"stop":2275.7,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2275.7,"stop":2275.964,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"The values described are not significant unless there is an impairment of beneficial use of the adjoining lands.","start":2275.964,"stop":2283.152,"duration":7.19},{"text":"It would not likely go to condemnation because the values are not significantly enough for that purpose.","start":2283.152,"stop":2288.773,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Normally when the sovereign is going to condemn land for a road or for any other purpose, the sovereign says, it shall be here.","start":2288.773,"stop":2296.113,"duration":7.34},{"text":"If none, devaluation is determined --","start":2296.113,"stop":2297.771,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2297.771,"stop":2298.497,"duration":0.73},{"text":"That is correct.","start":2298.497,"stop":2298.794,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"-- after that.","start":2298.794,"stop":2299.415,"duration":0.62},{"text":"The Court is -- or could it -- does a question, does the Court ordinarily in a condemnation get into the question of where the road shall be?","start":2299.415,"stop":2307.981,"duration":8.57}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2307.981,"stop":2309.34,"duration":1.36},{"text":"It does not.","start":2309.34,"stop":2309.866,"duration":0.53},{"text":"The United States --","start":2309.866,"stop":2310.352,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"The road is day to day, they -- the passageway is determined according to need and presumably the engineers take into account the most economical way to put the road in?","start":2310.352,"stop":2321.233,"duration":10.88}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the United States can take the road any point it thinks is in the best interest of the project and then damages are computed on the basis of the burden resulting to the private lands.","start":2321.233,"stop":2332.995,"duration":11.76},{"text":"Thank you Your Honor.","start":2332.995,"stop":2333.621,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you counsel.","start":2333.621,"stop":2334.393,"duration":0.77},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":2334.393,"stop":2337.515,"duration":3.12}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 15, 1979","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger6/oral_argument_audio/16181","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear argument next in Leo Sheep Company against United States.","start":0,"stop":33.111,"duration":33.11},{"text":"We'll wait until the stadium is cleared.","start":33.111,"stop":40.81,"duration":7.7}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice --","start":40.81,"stop":41.311,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Martz, I think you may continue your --proceed.","start":41.311,"stop":46.011,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":46.011,"stop":48.611,"duration":2.6},{"text":"The issue in this case is whether Congress reserved rights of way across some 34 million acres of land that were patented in support of the transcontinental railroad construction under the Union Pacific Act of 1862.","start":48.611,"stop":71.676,"duration":23.07},{"text":"The Act is very straightforward.","start":71.676,"stop":73.864,"duration":2.19},{"text":"Section 3 makes a grant of every alternate section of public land designated by odd numbers to the amount of five alternate sections per mile on each side of the railroad.","start":73.864,"stop":88.397,"duration":14.53},{"text":"This number was amended two years later to increase it to ten.","start":88.397,"stop":93.623,"duration":5.23},{"text":"The purpose is stated in Section 3 as aiding in the construction of said railroad and telegraph line and to secure the safe and speed transportation of the male troops, munitions of war in public stores thereon.Congress made three categories of exceptions.","start":93.623,"stop":116.456,"duration":22.83},{"text":"First is provided for an exception for land sold, reserved or otherwise disposed off by the United States prior to the fixing of the road.","start":116.456,"stop":128.579,"duration":12.12},{"text":"Secondly, it exempted or it excepted mineral lands.","start":128.579,"stop":132.613,"duration":4.03},{"text":"And third, it excluded or required a reversion of lands not sold or disposed off within three years after the completion of the road.","start":132.613,"stop":143.22,"duration":10.61},{"text":"It contain no exceptions or reservations of any kind for rights of way across the lands granted and this is not an issue or in dispute in the case.","start":143.22,"stop":154.656,"duration":11.44},{"text":"Section 4 then directed that after acceptance of each 40 miles of line constructed.","start":154.656,"stop":162.749,"duration":8.09},{"text":"Patent shall issue conveying the right and title of said lands to the company.","start":162.749,"stop":170.979,"duration":8.23},{"text":"And it provides no qualification with respect to the right or title of lands that are conveyed.","start":170.979,"stop":179.908,"duration":8.93},{"text":"Petitioners in this case are successors and enters to the railroad grants of Section 3 lands on the east side of Seminoe Reservoir in the State of Wyoming and have grants under Section 4 without reservation of any kind in the patents for crossing.","start":179.908,"stop":205.526,"duration":25.62},{"text":"Petitioners also hold the alternate, even-numbered sections under grazing license pursuant to the Taylor Grazing Act of 1934.","start":205.526,"stop":217.062,"duration":11.54},{"text":"The controversy in this case arose in December of 1973, when officers and agents of the Department of Interior commenced constructing a road from a public highway westerly to the eastern shore of Seminoe Reservoir across public domain sections and the alternating checkerboard lands of petitioner's patent that under the 1862 Act.","start":217.062,"stop":255.008,"duration":37.95},{"text":"They did this without consent of the landowners without payment of any compensation or fencing on the road for the protection of the lands crossed.","start":255.008,"stop":264.806,"duration":9.8},{"text":"Petitioners filed an action to quiet title against this claim.","start":264.806,"stop":269.839,"duration":5.03},{"text":"The parties stipulated as to the facts and submitted the matter to the Federal District Court in Wyoming for --on cross motions of summary judgment on the title issue.","start":269.839,"stop":283.134,"duration":13.3},{"text":"The District Court quieted title in the plaintiffs concluding that were no rights of way reserved either expressly or by implication.","start":283.134,"stop":295.285,"duration":12.15},{"text":"Secondly, that the --no rights of way by necessity could be implied in the favor of the sovereign since the sovereign has the power of eminent domain to take such ways as it needs all times.","start":295.285,"stop":312.697,"duration":17.41},{"text":"And the Court further found that for 110 years after the grant of the fee lands to the Union Pacific Railroad Company, neither the Department of the Interior nor any other agency or agent of the United States construed the grant or the patents issued pursuant thereto as conferring any right upon the United States as agents or the public to traverse the lands granted to the railroad.","start":312.697,"stop":341.831,"duration":29.13},{"text":"On appeal to the Tenth Circuit Court that decision was reversed, Court of Appeals finding that there was a right of way reserved by implication saying, To hold to the contrary would be to ascribe to Congress the degree of carelessness or lack of foresight which in our view would be unwarranted.","start":341.831,"stop":372.351,"duration":30.52},{"text":"Petitioner submit that the decision of this Court of Appeals should be reversed.","start":372.351,"stop":380.68,"duration":8.33},{"text":"The decision of the trial court affirmed for several reasons.","start":380.68,"stop":386.075,"duration":5.39},{"text":"The first and foremost being that the Court of Appeals presumed an intent that was not expressed anywhere by Congress in the legislative history or in the debates or in the language of the Act.","start":386.075,"stop":403.157,"duration":17.08},{"text":"The Court of Appeals considered no administrative experience under the Act in 110 years of patenting of lands.","start":403.157,"stop":414.74,"duration":11.58}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Just tell me what's been happening about this for a 110 years Mr. Martz?","start":414.74,"stop":419.508,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Brennan, absolutely nothing.","start":419.508,"stop":421.687,"duration":2.18},{"text":"The United States in his brief acknowledges that it has acquired rights of way by purchase when it's needed them.","start":421.687,"stop":429.694,"duration":8.01},{"text":"So far as the record shows, there has never been a condemnation action to acquire a right of way.","start":429.694,"stop":435.43,"duration":5.74},{"text":"It would appear Your Honor that this is a new idea that was --","start":435.43,"stop":438.776,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But --there must have been rights of way all this time?","start":438.776,"stop":441.802,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":441.802,"stop":442.392,"duration":0.59},{"text":"I think if we look at the history of the Union Pacific Act and the way in which this alternate section concept was used by Congress to encourage settlement and development of the lands and support the railroad --this becomes understandable.","start":442.392,"stop":462.822,"duration":20.43},{"text":"Congress started back in 1827, according to the legislative history, in providing support for public improvements by contributing the proceeds from the sale of public lands.","start":462.822,"stop":477.159,"duration":14.34},{"text":"It did this for canals, it did it for highways and it did it starting in 1850 for railroads.","start":477.159,"stop":484.672,"duration":7.51},{"text":"The idea was that it would give the proceeds of sale to an enterprise that was providing a public improvement.","start":484.672,"stop":494.858,"duration":10.19}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That got to be a very politically hot potato after awhile, isn't it?","start":494.858,"stop":498.508,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right Your Honor.","start":498.508,"stop":499.814,"duration":1.31},{"text":"And one response to the political hot potato was the checkerboard pattern.","start":499.814,"stop":504.123,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":504.123,"stop":506.107,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Congress was criticized for giving away land.","start":506.107,"stop":508.656,"duration":2.55},{"text":"So it theorized --","start":508.656,"stop":509.52,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Internal improvements that was coming --","start":509.52,"stop":511.599,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Internal improvements, yes.","start":511.599,"stop":513.39,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And everybody --","start":513.39,"stop":513.427,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"That if we were to --","start":513.427,"stop":514.198,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"--in Congress shied away from that phrase?","start":514.198,"stop":516.7,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":516.7,"stop":517.238,"duration":0.54},{"text":"And it provided that what we're going to do is subsidize the project with alternate sections and we retain the intervening section for sale for the public treasury and if settlement occurs and the country grows, the land retained can be sold for double value when we recover the price of the subsidy.","start":517.238,"stop":538.083,"duration":20.84}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":538.083,"stop":539.387,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, it look that the enterprise as promoting settlement through sale of lands concurrently with entries under the Preemption Acts of the alternate sections.","start":539.387,"stop":552.628,"duration":13.24},{"text":"And in the experience for 35 years, from 1827 to 1862, the lands were settled in the --along the canals and the highways without reservation of rights of way, without rights of way problems, and without creating a checkerboard pattern of land ownership.","start":552.628,"stop":574.9,"duration":22.27},{"text":"It is a case where a person settling on an odd section of land, pays one seller.","start":574.9,"stop":580.095,"duration":5.2},{"text":"He settles on an even section of land, he pays another.","start":580.095,"stop":584.074,"duration":3.98},{"text":"Now, this was the picture in 1862 --","start":584.074,"stop":586.518,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And of course, many roads were built across those kinds of land by the land authorities --","start":586.518,"stop":590.778,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":590.778,"stop":591.249,"duration":0.47},{"text":"The land was not --","start":591.249,"stop":593.588,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"--by state or local government and by condemnation.","start":593.588,"stop":597.535,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"And simply by the cooperative efforts of the settlers.","start":597.535,"stop":600.825,"duration":3.29},{"text":"As we know when people moved west to settle, they followed trails of convenience whether it went across public or private lands, was of no concern to either.","start":600.825,"stop":612.32,"duration":11.5},{"text":"There was a --as this Court has developed in the Buford case and the Camfield case that has come up with --under the Inclosures Act questions.","start":612.32,"stop":622.293,"duration":9.97},{"text":"It is recognized, a law of the open range where people had a right to push livestock, graze livestock on unfenced lands without regard to land ownerships.","start":622.293,"stop":637.634,"duration":15.34},{"text":"This was the plan but there's another fuzz of it.","start":637.634,"stop":641.826,"duration":4.19},{"text":"Congress wanted this transcontinental railroad.","start":641.826,"stop":645.643,"duration":3.82},{"text":"It had been trying to get it from the mid 1850s.","start":645.643,"stop":649.04,"duration":3.4},{"text":"It was a big gamble because there was nothing west to the Missouri but Indians and (Inaudible).","start":649.04,"stop":658.07,"duration":9.03},{"text":"The railroad was created by the Act, Union Pacific Road but it could not get private capital to support this gamble.","start":658.07,"stop":666.541,"duration":8.47},{"text":"This Court reviewed the pressures on Congress in the Platte case in 1879 and said strikingly, Enough\".","start":666.541,"stop":688.431,"duration":21.89},{"text":"\"We do not now attempt to portray the earnestness, the all absorbing earnestness with which Congress sought to secure the construction of the road by private enterprise\".","start":688.431,"stop":699.422,"duration":10.99},{"text":"In 1862, it gave five sections of land on either side of the road.","start":699.422,"stop":703.717,"duration":4.29},{"text":"In 1864, it increased it to ten sections.","start":703.717,"stop":707.059,"duration":3.34},{"text":"This Court said in Platte that was necessary to push the project.","start":707.059,"stop":711.922,"duration":4.86},{"text":"The Court said, Suffice it to say the purpose of Congress above all others was to obtain the construction of the railroad by the corporation that created to undertake the work\".","start":711.922,"stop":722.693,"duration":10.77},{"text":"For that alone, the subsidy bonds were given and only for that the grants of land were made.","start":722.693,"stop":729.672,"duration":6.98}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It was British Capital that finally built the Union Pacific, wasn't it?","start":729.672,"stop":733.603,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"I --I'm not aware of that.","start":733.603,"stop":734.643,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"It was Greenville Dodge who is behind it, wasn't it?","start":734.643,"stop":737.051,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"What's what sir?","start":737.051,"stop":737.579,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn't Greenville Dodge who is behind it from Omaha?","start":737.579,"stop":740.701,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't have that (Voice Overlap) for it.","start":740.701,"stop":742.437,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"He gave guys money for it.","start":742.437,"stop":744.072,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Does this record --","start":744.072,"stop":744.653,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":744.653,"stop":745.41,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"-- shows to much, to what extent the rights of way were taken by condemnation either federal or state over this whole history that is I don't mean precisely, was --","start":745.41,"stop":760.25,"duration":14.84}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there --","start":760.25,"stop":760.301,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"--was there a lot of right of way and a lot of money or just a small amount?","start":760.301,"stop":765.752,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":765.752,"stop":765.949,"duration":0.2},{"text":"As far --you may --are you speaking of the private condemnation or Government condemnation to get the rights of way across these tracks.","start":765.949,"stop":772.165,"duration":6.22},{"text":"As far as the record shows Your Honor in all three levels of court, there has not been a condemnation proceeding initiated by the United States.","start":772.165,"stop":784.594,"duration":12.43},{"text":"At least none has been brought to the attention of any Court by the Government.","start":784.594,"stop":792.057,"duration":7.46}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a little puzzling why this has taken so long to mature into this situation, isn't it?","start":792.057,"stop":798.245,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, may I suggest that as the lands were in fact settled in the west, if we leave out the checkerboard pattern for a moment.","start":798.245,"stop":810.123,"duration":11.88},{"text":"You do had as Mr. Justice Stewart suggested, had a day to day, week to week evolution of road or trail construction which trails became road by prescriptive easement.","start":810.123,"stop":825.087,"duration":14.96},{"text":"The land was not of great value and access was --","start":825.087,"stop":828.237,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, later it became --some of it became very valuable timberland, isn't it, and as today is that not so?","start":828.237,"stop":834.371,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this happened, yes, through the years when rights of way might be purchased.","start":834.371,"stop":842.776,"duration":8.4},{"text":"I recalled, this Court said in the Camfield case of every landowner has a right to enclose his own land and obviously, if he does this, this man interfere with access to the other lands.","start":842.776,"stop":855.233,"duration":12.46},{"text":"But the Court said, This can't really be a practical problem until such time as the west is fully settled and at that point there will be roads to the union\".","start":855.233,"stop":865.866,"duration":10.63}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Martz --","start":865.866,"stop":867.259,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":867.259,"stop":869.228,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"--as a practical matter, how much are we really talking about in this case, the Leo Sheep Company?","start":869.228,"stop":876.149,"duration":6.92},{"text":"A part from your parade of horribles in your brief but all we're talking about is an easement across the corners, isn't it?","start":876.149,"stop":883.259,"duration":7.11}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that is right Your Honor.","start":883.259,"stop":883.987,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Much money involved?","start":883.987,"stop":885.2,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"We are talking of very few dollars.","start":885.2,"stop":888.03,"duration":2.83},{"text":"We're talking only about a principle that if this checkerboard lands were patented without reservation.","start":888.03,"stop":896.459,"duration":8.43},{"text":"The issue today is not really whether the United States or any other private party has a right of access to cross a section of land to reach an adjoining section of land.","start":896.459,"stop":910.157,"duration":13.7},{"text":"The kind of case in which this question is being raised is precisely the kind that gave rise to this controversy, the construction of a roadway across a ranch area for access not of a few people but of the public to a recreational area without fencing the road for the protection of the integrity of the ranching area.","start":910.157,"stop":934.661,"duration":24.5},{"text":"These are the kind of questions in which this issue will be raised and it's on these kinds of questions that we need clarification of these rights.","start":934.661,"stop":944.589,"duration":9.93}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Martz, following up on Justice Blackmun's question.","start":944.589,"stop":948.917,"duration":4.33},{"text":"Is it not true, if you look at the checkerboard that it would always be possible to get from --to stay on Government land except where you have to cross at corners, you could --","start":948.917,"stop":957.131,"duration":8.21}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":957.131,"stop":957.92,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So that --isn't it possible that Congress --you've mentioned the widespread understanding that people could post any place they wanted to in the west in those days without worrying about having someone build a fence in front of them.","start":957.92,"stop":968.524,"duration":10.6},{"text":"Isn't likely that Congress didn't dream that there'd been any problem of cutting across a corner every mile or so?","start":968.524,"stop":973.835,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I would submit that Congress didn't dream that there would be checkerboard ownership of the land --","start":973.835,"stop":981.936,"duration":8.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they knew there would be --","start":981.936,"stop":981.973,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"-- through the support program.","start":981.973,"stop":982.995,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at least to start with.","start":982.995,"stop":985.401,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":985.401,"stop":986.876,"duration":1.48},{"text":"It already had 35 years of experience in entering lands in the alternate section basis.","start":986.876,"stop":995.755,"duration":8.88},{"text":"Had the railroads in moving west followed the provisions of the Act and obtained patents as they've completed each 40-mile piece of land and sold those lands off to settlers to raise money to continue to build the road as it happen with the canal program in the east.","start":995.755,"stop":1015.849,"duration":20.09},{"text":"You would have scattered settlements on odd and even numbered sections.","start":1015.849,"stop":1022.717,"duration":6.87},{"text":"The same as you would have under the homestead process.","start":1022.717,"stop":1027.124,"duration":4.41},{"text":"What happened that Congress could not have anticipated in 1862 when it enacted the Homestead Act opening the west and that Railroad Grant Act for the Union Pacific Road was that for the first time the public enterprise would not sell the land to settlers but would mortgage it in its entireties.","start":1027.124,"stop":1051.767,"duration":24.64},{"text":"It was the mortgaging process that created a pattern of checkerboard ownership that became a matter of concern 10 years after the grants were first made.","start":1051.767,"stop":1063.797,"duration":12.03}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Martz, am I wrong in thinking the Homestead Act of 1862 authorized only a 160-acre homesteads?","start":1063.797,"stop":1071.144,"duration":7.35}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right Your Honor.","start":1071.144,"stop":1072.396,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"I am correct in this.","start":1072.396,"stop":1073.101,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1073.101,"stop":1074.048,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"And why -- was it the Desert Land Act in 1877 or the farmer's stock or like 1960 --","start":1074.048,"stop":1080.068,"duration":6.02}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"In the --","start":1080.068,"stop":1080.249,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"--and it finally went to 640?","start":1080.249,"stop":1081.645,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there was an enlarged Homestead Act first and I can't give you the data, 1890 or 1900.","start":1081.645,"stop":1089.037,"duration":7.39},{"text":"I don't know, the Stock Raising Homestead Act went to 640.","start":1089.037,"stop":1091.741,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But in any rate, at the time of these railroad grants, the homestead was a 160 and not 640?","start":1091.741,"stop":1097.351,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, it was really contemporaneous that Congress had had no experience under the Homestead Act.","start":1097.351,"stop":1103.075,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"They had passed at the same time?","start":1103.075,"stop":1104.022,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"It passed the same Congress and that --and homestead access were opening the west.","start":1104.022,"stop":1108.33,"duration":4.31},{"text":"You can settle in a 160-acre family units.","start":1108.33,"stop":1112.768,"duration":4.44},{"text":"It said to the railroads, \"We're granting alternate sections to you for you to dispose of\".","start":1112.768,"stop":1118.142,"duration":5.37},{"text":"It did not to be sure limit the size of the disposition but it did say any lands which have not been disposed of in three years after the completion of the road will then be open to entry only under the homestead in preemption laws.","start":1118.142,"stop":1137.499,"duration":19.36},{"text":"So Congress was looking at the sale of lands while the railroad was being constructed and the residual lands would become part of the public domain package.","start":1137.499,"stop":1153.988,"duration":16.49},{"text":"And it --","start":1153.988,"stop":1154.099,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And what the railroads did was to sell them to their own subsidiaries, isn't they?","start":1154.099,"stop":1157.437,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"They --the railroads were engaged in a great deal of fraud --at least they were charged with a great deal of --","start":1157.437,"stop":1164.545,"duration":7.11}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Charged with that.","start":1164.545,"stop":1165.52,"duration":0.97},{"text":"Yes.","start":1165.52,"stop":1166.635,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"--of fraud.","start":1166.635,"stop":1167.481,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But there were a lot of --","start":1167.481,"stop":1168.597,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"To a point where Congress and this is most significant to that after the problem of the checkerboard grants became very real during the range wars of the 1880s and 1890s where as you say, let these packages lands were transferred to subsidiaries or to private companies who tried to utilize the checkerboard pattern of ownership to seize control of great amounts of the public lands.","start":1168.597,"stop":1198.638,"duration":30.04}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1198.638,"stop":1199.588,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"And led to the enactment of the Unlawful Inclosures Act in 1885.","start":1199.588,"stop":1205.338,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1205.338,"stop":1206.829,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"And it led Congress in 1887 to affirm the titles of bona fide purchasers from the railroads.","start":1206.829,"stop":1220.713,"duration":13.88},{"text":"Had Congress had any reservation at all as to whether it had or had not made a reservation of rights of way in 1862?","start":1220.713,"stop":1230.905,"duration":10.19},{"text":"It certainly had the right when it affirmed the patents of bona fide purchasers in 1887 declare that.","start":1230.905,"stop":1238.283,"duration":7.38}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But how do I just as an individual apply all of that which came about at the time to quote you, there was none beyond Missouri but (Inaudible) Indians when at the time when California was the largest State in the Union.","start":1238.283,"stop":1253.512,"duration":15.23}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1253.512,"stop":1254.203,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean to bring it down to me.","start":1254.203,"stop":1254.923,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1254.923,"stop":1255.355,"duration":0.43},{"text":"To be sure Mr. Justice Marshall, they were not --have built the railroad.","start":1255.355,"stop":1257.822,"duration":2.47},{"text":"They --","start":1257.822,"stop":1257.853,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think of myself, I mean --","start":1257.853,"stop":1259.387,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1259.387,"stop":1259.728,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I just (Voice Overlap) --","start":1259.728,"stop":1260.715,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"But it was the area between where --what were --that the theory was that the grants of these lands would --","start":1260.715,"stop":1266.552,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I have great difficulty with the United States Government giving away my land without retaining an easement?","start":1266.552,"stop":1274.727,"duration":8.18}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1274.727,"stop":1275.831,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it did not retain easements in homestead grants.","start":1275.831,"stop":1281.953,"duration":6.12},{"text":"As a matter fact United States has not retained an easement of this kind in any grant.","start":1281.953,"stop":1287.202,"duration":5.25},{"text":"As this Court said in Platte, the purpose of the grants was to support the road.","start":1287.202,"stop":1292.62,"duration":5.42},{"text":"It was to enable the railroad to sell these lands to settlers moving along the road west and using the money for the construction of road.","start":1292.62,"stop":1302.972,"duration":10.35},{"text":"Now, if Congress allowed homesteads on even-numbered sections without any reservation of right and said on the odd-numbered section you, Mr. Railroad, you've got to give us an easement undefined across that land.","start":1302.972,"stop":1321.744,"duration":18.77},{"text":"How successful would the railroad have been in competing with the Homestead Act in selling any lands, assuming the lands were off equal quality?","start":1321.744,"stop":1331.648,"duration":9.9},{"text":"The purpose, this Court said in Platte was to support the railroad and to settle the west.","start":1331.648,"stop":1340.015,"duration":8.37},{"text":"That the three-judge dissenting opinion in Platte is I think very helpful in getting this whole matter in focus.","start":1340.015,"stop":1351.742,"duration":11.73},{"text":"This was a Court speaking at the time when congressional intent was still fresh efore in everybody's mind.","start":1351.742,"stop":1360.057,"duration":8.32},{"text":"The majority in Platte allowed the railroads to hold this acreage on the theory that the mortgaging was a disposition so that within the three years after completion of the road, the railroad didn't have to either settled it or give it back for entry under the homestead or preemption laws, it could held it.","start":1360.057,"stop":1384.617,"duration":24.56},{"text":"The dissent in Platte said, \"This is not what Congress ever intended.","start":1384.617,"stop":1390.161,"duration":5.54},{"text":"Congress intended these lands to be settled and that the railroads would not be able to hold them by mortgage.It could not hold this land locked checkerboard patterned\".","start":1390.161,"stop":1401.803,"duration":11.64},{"text":"And had the will of Congress been carried out without the mortgaging process, we wouldn't have these problems today.","start":1401.803,"stop":1410.365,"duration":8.56},{"text":"But the fact remains the lands were patented.","start":1410.365,"stop":1416.519,"duration":6.15},{"text":"There was no reservation.","start":1416.519,"stop":1418.969,"duration":2.45},{"text":"The legislative history would affirmed the fact that there was no intent on the part of Congress to make such reservation.","start":1418.969,"stop":1429.97,"duration":11},{"text":"Now that --I want to save five minutes for rebuttal but I want to make one comment about the two pieces that the Court of Appeals used not as precedent but as comfort in support of its decision, this being the Buford case and the Camfield case that came up with respect to the practices that were then in existence of getting monopolies on the public lands by use of this checkerboard acreage.","start":1429.97,"stop":1458.82,"duration":28.85},{"text":"Buford said, No private landowner can enjoin or recovery trespass damage for the crossing of unfenced open lands associated with the public domain.","start":1458.82,"stop":1474.069,"duration":15.25},{"text":"Camfield said, It's a public nuisance for the holder of checkerboard lands to fence it and thereby even though the fences are on private lands enclosed blocks the public domain\".","start":1474.069,"stop":1489.23,"duration":15.16}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Camfield was base on Act of Congress so specified, wasn't it?","start":1489.23,"stop":1493.321,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Clyde O. Martz","textObjs":[{"text":"The Act of Congress saying, \"There shall not be an enclosure\".","start":1493.321,"stop":1497.14,"duration":3.82},{"text":"The point gentleman I want to make is that that in both of the Acts and both of the cases.","start":1497.14,"stop":1504.293,"duration":7.15},{"text":"Looking first at Buford, this Court made it clear that what it was speaking off is the custom of the open range and it lasted for a hundred years that you cross land whether in public or private ownership, in cattle drives or with grazing without liability and trespass or without hindrance.","start":1504.293,"stop":1531.262,"duration":26.97},{"text":"If the private landowner wanted to protect his land, he had to fence it.","start":1531.262,"stop":1537.969,"duration":6.71},{"text":"And this Court said in Camfield, \"If he fences it, he is entitled to exclusive possession\".","start":1537.969,"stop":1544.715,"duration":6.75},{"text":"Now, the court below and the Government said --have argued, that these cases suggest the existence of rights of way across the odd-numbered sections because --","start":1544.715,"stop":1557.751,"duration":13.04}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll resume there at 10 o'clock in the morning officer.","start":1557.751,"stop":1569.229,"duration":11.48}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Jan  15 - 16, 1979","petitioner":"Leo Sheep Company","respondent":"United States","docket":"77-1686","citation":"440US668(1979)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/440/668","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Mar 27, 1979"}